Problem Statement¶

One of a prominent Food industry plant in Canada require their employees to wear masks while contacting with food so curb the spread any kind of contamination. Hence, it is a very tedius task to keep in check the employees all the time. Secondly, a covid outbreak is detrimental to the operation of the company as everyone works in a close net circle. Therefore, it is required to develop an automated mask detection system to ensure that everyone wears the masks.

Mask detection models typically use computer vision techniques to identify faces in images or video frames, and then analyze those faces to determine whether or not a mask is present. Deep learning models, in particular, have been shown to be very effective at this task. These models typically use convolutional neural networks (CNNs) to analyze the images, and may also use other techniques such as data augmentation, transfer learning, and fine-tuning to improve their accuracy.

Data Exploration¶

We used two datasets from Kaggle.

https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/andrewmvd/face-mask-detection¶

This dataset contains 853 images belonging to the 3 classes (With mask;Without mask;Mask worn incorrectly), as well as their bounding boxes in the PASCAL VOC format.

https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/ashishjangra27/face-mask-12k-images-dataset¶

This dataset is used for Face Mask Detection Classification with images. The dataset consists of almost 12K images which are almost 328.92MB in size. With three directories, train(10000);test(800);validation(800), the images are equally classified to two labels, withmask and withoutmask.

The function "face_cas" is to visualizes the detections using rectangles and labels. The function takes an image file name as input and reads the corresponding XML file that contains the annotations for the image. The function uses the xmltodict library to parse the XML file into a dictionary.¶
In [46]:
def face_cas(img):
    with open(path_annotations+img[:-4]+".xml") as fd:
        doc=xmltodict.parse(fd.read())
    image=plt.imread(os.path.join(path_images+img))
    fig,ax=plt.subplots(1)
    ax.axis("off")
    fig.set_size_inches(10,5)
    temp=doc["annotation"]["object"]
    if type(temp)==list:
        for i in range(len(temp)):
            ###with_mask
            if temp[i]["name"]=="with_mask":
                x,y,w,h=list(map(int,temp[i]["bndbox"].values()))
                mpatch=mpatches.Rectangle((x,y),w-x,h-y,linewidth=1, edgecolor='g',facecolor="none",lw=2,)
                ax.add_patch(mpatch)
                rx, ry = mpatch.get_xy()
                ax.annotate("with_mask", (rx, ry), color='green', weight='bold', fontsize=10, ha='left', va='baseline')
            ###without_mask
            if temp[i]["name"]=="without_mask":
                x,y,w,h=list(map(int,temp[i]["bndbox"].values()))
                mpatch=mpatches.Rectangle((x,y),w-x,h-y,linewidth=1, edgecolor='r',facecolor="none",lw=2,)
                ax.add_patch(mpatch)
                rx, ry = mpatch.get_xy()
                ax.annotate("without_mask", (rx, ry), color='red', weight='bold', fontsize=10, ha='left', va='baseline')
            ###mask_weared_incorrect
            if temp[i]["name"]=="mask_weared_incorrect":
                x,y,w,h=list(map(int,temp[i]["bndbox"].values()))
                mpatch=mpatches.Rectangle((x,y),w-x,h-y,linewidth=1, edgecolor='y',facecolor="none",lw=2,)
                ax.add_patch(mpatch)
                rx, ry = mpatch.get_xy()
                ax.annotate("mask_weared_incorrect", (rx, ry), color='yellow', weight='bold', fontsize=10, ha='left', va='baseline')
    else:
        x,y,w,h=list(map(int,temp["bndbox"].values()))
        edgecolor={"with_mask":"g","without_mask":"r","mask_weared_incorrect":"y"}
        mpatch=mpatches.Rectangle((x,y),w-x,h-y,linewidth=1, edgecolor=edgecolor[temp["name"]],facecolor="none",)
    ax.imshow(image)
    ax.add_patch(mpatch)

Haarcascade_frontalfaces a pre-trained cascade classifier in OpenCV for detecting frontal faces in images or video frames. The classifier is based on the Haar-like features algorithm, which is a type of feature descriptor used in computer vision for object detection.

The function “detect_mask” is to uses a pre-trained deep learning model to detect faces in an image and classify them as wearing a mask or not. The function takes two inputs: the input image and the pre-trained deep learning model.¶
In [52]:
mask_label = {0:'MASK',1:'NO MASK'}
color_label = {0:(0,255,0),1:(255,0,0)}
In [53]:
def detect_mask(img,model):
    img = cv2.cvtColor(img, cv2.IMREAD_GRAYSCALE)
    #face_model = cv2.CascadeClassifier(r"D:\ana\envs\tensorflow_test\Lib\site-packages\cv2\data\haarcascade_frontalface_default.xml")
    faces = face_model.detectMultiScale(img,scaleFactor=1.1, minNeighbors=3)
    if len(faces)>=1:
        new_img = cv2.cvtColor(img, cv2.COLOR_RGB2BGR)
        for i in range(len(faces)):
            (x,y,w,h) = faces[i]
            crop = new_img[y:y+h,x:x+w]
            crop = cv2.resize(crop,(128,128))
            crop = np.reshape(crop,[1,128,128,3])/255.0
            mask_result = model.predict(crop)
            cv2.putText(new_img,mask_label[mask_result.argmax()],(x, y-10),cv2.FONT_HERSHEY_SIMPLEX,0.5,color_label[mask_result.argmax()],2)
            cv2.rectangle(new_img,(x,y),(x+w,y+h),color_label[mask_result.argmax()],1)
        plt.figure(figsize=(10,10))
        plt.imshow(new_img)

    else:
        print("No. of faces detected is less than 1")

Prepare the data¶

We implement ImageDataGenerator in Keras to generate batches of image data with real-time data augmentation. We apply various image transformations such as shearing, zooming, shifting, to augment the available image data to increase the diversity of the dataset and prevent overfitting.

We use pre-trained cnn model to test our process and choose vgg. VGG stands for Visual Geometry Group; it is a standard deep Convolutional Neural Network (CNN) architecture with multiple layers. The “deep” refers to the number of layers with VGG-19 consisting of19 convolutional layers.¶

In this notebook we are using the VGG19 pre-trained model.¶

It is quite similar to the VGG16 model, with the only difference being that it has three extra convolution layers.¶

Conclusion¶

Num Filters: The number of filters is the Depth of the output feature map, computed by the convolution. 32 filters have enough capacity to learn complex representations of this input data. Too many filters may overfit to the training data.

Activation: Data has shown that ReLU outperforms sigmoid in deep neural networks, particularly in image classification tasks. This is partly due to the fact that ReLU can better handle large and complex datasets, and partly due to its ability to capture more complex patterns and representations in the input data. Also, it is more computationally efficient and avoids the vanishing gradient problem(Check the train loss up there)

Learning Rate: A smaller learning rate has an overwhelming advantage. Apparently, small step size allows the optimizer to carefully search the parameter space and avoid overshooting the optimal solution. When the learning rate is too large, the optimizer may oscillate around the optimal solution or even diverge.

Epoches: We don't see more epoches make obvious difference. The models become overfitting in less than 10 epoches. That's why we apply early stoping in model training.
